        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>The <strong>Logitech Brio 4K</strong> is the direct competitor at the same $149 price. It offers 4K30 resolution and Windows Hello IR facial recognition, which the Kiyo Pro lacks. But its low-light performance is noticeably worse, its 1080p60 is compressed (not uncompressed like the Kiyo Pro), and it has a smaller footprint but no privacy cap. If 4K and Windows Hello matter to you, the Brio wins. If low-light and smooth 60fps matter more, the Kiyo Pro wins. See our <a href="/reviews/logitech-brio-4k-review/">Logitech Brio 4K review</a> for the full breakdown.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Logitech C920x</strong> is the budget champion at $60. It produces a clean 1080p30 image in good lighting, works plug-and-play, and has been the default streaming webcam for a decade. But its low-light performance is poor — at 50 lux, the image is a noisy, gray mess. If you have good lighting, the C920x covers 80% of what the Kiyo Pro does for 40% of the price. If you do not have good lighting, the Kiyo Pro is the fix.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Insta360 Link</strong> is the premium pick at $299. It offers 4K30, a motorized gimbal for AI tracking, and excellent low-light performance that rivals the Kiyo Pro. But it costs twice as much, and its tracking features require the Insta360 software running at all times. If you want the best webcam regardless of price, the Insta360 Link is the pick. If you want the best 1080p webcam for the price, the Kiyo Pro wins.</p>

      <p>Pair the Kiyo Pro with a <a href="/reviews/benq-screenbar-halo-review/">monitor light bar</a> — front-facing lighting makes any webcam look better, and even the Kiyo Pro benefits from a well-lit face. For the broader category, see our <a href="/reviews/best-webcam-remote-work/">best webcam for remote work</a> roundup.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Buy the Kiyo Pro if you stream or take calls in lighting that is not studio-grade. Its larger sensor produces clean images where every other 1080p webcam produces noise, and that single advantage justifies the $149 price for anyone whose lighting is less than ideal.</p>

      <p>Make sure you have a USB 3.0 port. The Kiyo Pro's uncompressed 1080p60 signal requires USB 3.0 bandwidth — a USB 2.0 port caps you at 1080p30 with compression, which negates the main reason to buy it. Check your port specs before ordering, and if you only have USB-C, budget $10 for a USB-A to USB-C adapter or a dedicated USB-C cable.</p>

      <p>Install Synapse for firmware updates, then ignore it. The first thing to do after unboxing is install Razer Synapse, run the firmware updater, and then set Synapse to not launch at startup. Core features work without it, and the software is heavier than it needs to be. You only need it again if you want AI face tracking or custom presets.</p>

      <p>Set the FOV to 90° for most uses. 80° is too tight unless you want a headshot-only frame, and 103° introduces visible fish-eye distortion at the edges. 90° is the natural default — your face and shoulders with some background context, minimal distortion, and a flattering perspective.</p>

      <p>Skip the Kiyo Pro if you need 4K. The Insta360 Link and Logitech Brio 4K both offer 4K30, and for recording footage you will edit and upscale, 4K is worth the extra resolution. For live streaming and video calls, 1080p60 is more than enough — the smoother motion matters more than the extra pixels.</p>

      <p>Avoid no-name $30 webcams on Amazon. They claim 1080p but deliver interpolated 720p with cheap sensors that turn to noise in any lighting below studio-grade. The Kiyo Pro is the floor for acceptable low-light performance; below it, you are wasting your money on a webcam you will replace within months.</p>

